<br>
1 parchment = 1/16 chance of xxspell<br>
2 parchments = 2/16 chance of xxspell<br>
3 parchments = 3/16 chance of xxspell<br>
<br>
NO NO NO<br>
<br>
1 parchment = 1/16 chance of xxspell<br>
2 parchments = 2/32 chance of xxspell<br>
3 parchments = 3/48 chance of xxspell<br>
<br>
Each parchment itself hase a 1/16 chance of being xxspell, but 16 parchments doesn't guarentee you 16/16 chance of getting xxspell (meaning you will get 1 of each, and the 1 you want 100%).  Instead your chances are worse, you have a 16/256 chance if you turn in 16 parchments (which is still 1/16).  The RNG is more than likely &quot;Working As Intended&quot; and as such, is flawed by design (which few would ever dispute).<br>
<br>
VI really should look into reworking the RNG to be less randomn and closer to the way it was designed to work (which it was designed to EVENLY distribute spells, not overload few spells).<br>
<br>
where xxspell=spell you want<br>
<br>
All fractional chances are based on the assumption that the all 16 spells carry the same weight in the RNG (or %'age of return), which is more than likely not the case, pets should obviously carry a heavier weight than the focus items (less % chance), but what good does it do to the community as a whole to have 600 61-62 mages, 1200 coppies of 61-62 focus items, 300 copies of 61-62 pets, etc.  What would they hope to accomplish by allowing the RNG to continue pumping out uneeded spells, it weakens the economy (since every 61+ mage has 4+ coppies of focus items before they finally get all 16 of 61 and 62 spells, there is no economy for the duplicates at this point).<br>
<br>
Then again, I ain't stressing about it personally, I am taking what I get, passing what I don't need and aa'ing in the meantime.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dabrighter2>Dabrighter2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 58<br> <font color=#333333>(1/6/03 6:14:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1749.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Number Generator (NG)</span><hr size=1> Quit calling EQ's Number Gererator (NG) a Random Number Generator (RNG).  It isn't.  There NG is so streaky, especially on events with a small probablity, that it can't be Pseudo-Randon.  I would not be surprised that EQ's NG has a chance to use the same number again or generate a new number.  When my med skill was at 220, it did not skill up for an entire level.  At the time I was hunting bloodgill goblins and was getting a level bout every 3 hours.  I was meding at least 75% of the time. Then, just after leveling, I got a string of 4 skill ups and then within a minute another string of 3 skill ups.  Using these numbers, assuming a random number pattern, it would be 3 hours * 60 minutes * 60 seconds/ 6 secs per tic *0.75 percent time = 1 skillup per 1350 tics or ~ 0.005 chance of a skillup per tic.  The chances of getting 3 skillups in a row is 0.000000128408906 or 1 in 7.78 million.  Can happen.  The chances of getting 4 skillups in a row is 0.000000000647829 or 1 in ~ 1543.6 million. That is 100 times rarer that wining the Powerball in the six state lottery.  The chances that both happening in a 5 minute period, while difficult to calculate, is extremely large.  The EQ's NG is not Random.  The streakyness of the the NG is easy to tell when doing something with a small propability of sucess.  I used get giants low to health and then chase them method to get my 1hb for 10 to 17.  It took me almost a full hour of chasing it.  I got skillups of two in a row, three in a row, and the two in a row again.  If the NG was random, two skillups in a row would be very rare, not the most common occurance.  <br>
